#-----------------------------------------------------------------------
BASIC KENEYSIAN MODEL

PLANNED AGGREGATE EXPENDITURE, PAE
    = Flow of total PLANNED spending, in aggregate, on final goods and services
    !!! PLANNED spending is not necessarily was is spent !!! 
        - household
        - firms 
        - government
        - foreign sectors

AGGREGATE EXPENDITURE, AE = Y
AGGREGATE OUTPUT, AO = Y
    = aggregate output (produced by firms)          <-- What firms are expecting to sell
    = The flow of total ACTUAL spending, in aggregate on final goods and services
    !!! ACTUAL spending may be higher or lower than PLANNED expenditure

SHORT RUN MACROECONOMIC EQUILIRIUM
    !!! Equilibrium = when economy is at rest?
    = A situation in which all spending plans are realised exactly, i.e. PAE = Y
        - What firm produces is what is being sold

SHORT RUN MACROECONOMIC DISEQUILIBRIUM
    = A situation in which all spending plans are not realised exactly,
        - PAE > Y ==> firms UNEXPECTEDLY decrease inventories   (demand much stronger than anticipated)
        - PAE < Y ==> firms UNEXPECTEDLY increase inventories   (demand is weaker than anticipated, lot of unsold goods!)
     

Y                                                   <-- GDP
    = AE                                            <-- Aggregate Expenditure
    = PAE + unexpected changes in inventories       <-- .... + UNEXPECTED INVESTMENT, Iu
    = Cd +Ip +G +X +Iu                              <-- I = planned investment, Ip + unexpected investment, Iu
    !!! MODEL SIMPLIFICATION: Assume that households, government, foreigners always have their plans realised
    !!! MODEL SIMPLIFICATION: Assume that firms may or may not have their plans realised 

(Next video - Lecture 5)

Model: 2d plot PAE=f(Y)
    - draw the 45 degree line                       <-- important line, where Y=PAE     (points of equilibrium!)
    - Plot the potential GDP, Y*                    <-- Y* is coming from 'growth economics', determined from outside the model (i.e. an exogenous variable)

!!! Exogenous variable = a variable determined from outside of the model
    ex: Potential GDP, Y*, determined by forces outside of the short run model
!!! An endogenous Variable = a variable determined from within the model (built in the model)
    ==> Model explain the variable
    ex: PAE=f(Y) equilibrium is endogenous
!!! Keynes: In the short run, Endogenous and exogenous equilibrium need not be the same
One of Keynesâ€™ insight into the economy was that the endogenous forces that determine equilibrium may not be related to the exogenous forces that determine potential GDP.

